cobalt-59 is produce by bombarding stable cobalt-56 with neutrons or alpha particles. The most common isotope of cobalt, cobalt-56, is stable and does not undergo radioactive decay. When cobalt-56 is bombarded with neutrons or alpha particles, it is converted into the radioactive isotope cobalt-59. Cobalt-59 has a half-life of 5.27 years and decays into nickel-59.
